<h1>CHAPTER 4: SYSTEM IMPLEMENTATION AND TESTING</h1>

<h2>4.1 Technologies and Tools Used</h2>
<p>The KaviCakes Management System is a full-stack solution built around three core components: the Admin Web Dashboard, the Customer Web Portal, and a centralized REST API Backend. All frontend components communicate through HTTPS-secured REST API calls to a single backend server, ensuring that business logic, variant pricing, and security enforcement remain in one controlled environment regardless of which interface sends the request.</p>
<p>The production system utilizes a localized storage architecture for operational files such as payment deposit slips, while leveraging Supabase storage buckets for preserving legacy product imagery. The backend connects securely to a MySQL relational database to maintain data persistence and referential integrity across financial records.</p>

<h2>4.2 Programming Languages and Development Tools</h2>

<h3>4.2.1 Backend — Node.js and Express.js</h3>
<p>The REST API is built on Node.js using the Express.js framework, chosen for its non-blocking I/O model that efficiently handles concurrent order placement and inventory requests. The database schema is managed by Prisma ORM, which provides compile-time type safety and prevents the schema from drifting out of sync with application code. Passwords are hashed using Bcryptjs with 10 salt rounds and are never stored in plaintext. Authentication is stateless and JWT-based. OTP codes for account activation are generated dynamically and expire after 10 minutes. A custom role-based middleware enforces access control on every protected endpoint before any database query is executed. File uploads (like payment slips) are handled by Multer directly to the server's local storage capabilities. Transactional emails are sent via Nodemailer configured securely with an SMTP service. Automated background tasks are managed by node-cron, specifically triggering daily at 08:00 AM to process 48-hour delivery reminders.</p>

<h3>4.2.2 Admin Web — React and Vite</h3>
<p>The Admin Dashboard is a Single Page Application built with React, bundled by Vite for fast development and optimized production builds. The user interface is built on Ant Design, providing accessible enterprise-grade components for forms, dynamic tables, side drawers, and standardized date pickers. Dashboard statistics are processed utilizing component states to display live KPIs representing today’s orders, pending advances, and generated income. Global layouts utilize React Router for navigation, and Axios interceptors automatically attach the JWT token and route users to the login screen upon encountering a 401 Unauthorized response.</p>

<h3>4.2.3 Customer Web — React and Vite</h3>
<p>The Customer Web Portal is also built utilizing React and Vite but completely isolates the styling architecture by employing Tailwind CSS. This provides a highly customized, mobile-first boutique aesthetic distinct from the administrative interface. Context API manages global states for the user session (`AuthContext`) and the active shopping session (`CartContext`). Complex components handle dynamic state calculations in real-time, such as the variant price calculator that immediately updates visually when a customer toggles between different cake sizes or flavors.</p>

<h2>4.3 User Interface Demonstration and Data Entry Screens</h2>
<p>The system interface is strictly organized by role. An Admin has access to all operational pipelines, cashbooks, and inventory matrices. A Customer sees exclusively their personal profile, the product catalog, and their own tracking histories. This isolation is enforced in the React frontend through route guards and in the backend API through middleware restricting data retrieval.</p>

<h3>4.3.1 Authentication</h3>
<p>Registration demands validation via a generated 6-digit OTP dispatched to the registered email before account initialization. Passwords mandate strict format policies evaluated instantly via real-time frontend Regex. For administrative access, attempting to authenticate a standard customer account across the restricted admin endpoints returns immediate HTTP access denial forcing route redirection natively maintaining system isolation.</p>
